To fix the issue where the modal backdrop remains visible even after closing the modal, you can utilize the Bootstrap Modal methods to control the modal behavior properly.

Here's what you can do:

1. Add a `ref` to the modal element:
   ```html
   <div
     v-if="modalShow && isEditable"
     id="userModal"
     class="modal fade"
     tabindex="-1"
     aria-labelledby="userModalLabel"
     aria-hidden="true"
     ref="userModal"
   >
   ```

2. Update the `modalShow` variable in your Vue script:
   ```javascript
   const modalShow = ref(true);

   // Close the modal and reset the backdrop
   const closeModal = () => {
     modalShow.value = false;

     // Reset the backdrop manually
     const modalElement = app.$refs.userModal;
     if (modalElement) {
       $(modalElement).modal("hide");
       $(modalElement).on("hidden.bs.modal", function () {
         $(".modal-backdrop").remove();
       });
     }
   };
   ```

   The `closeModal` function ensures that when the modal is closed, the `modalShow` value is set to `false`. Then, it uses the `jQuery` functions provided by Bootstrap to manually hide the modal and remove the backdrop.

   Make sure to replace `app` with your Vue app variable if it is named differently.

3. Update the close button inside the modal header:
   ```html
   <button
     type="button"
     class="btn-close"
     data-bs-dismiss="modal"
     aria-label="Close"
     @click="closeModal"
   ></button>
   ```

   By adding the `@click` event handler to the close button, we can call the `closeModal` function to close the modal and reset the backdrop.

With these changes, the modal should properly close and remove the backdrop, making the screen accessible again.

Please note that this solution assumes you are using Bootstrap and jQuery. If you are using a different modal library or approach, the implementation might differ slightly.

